\noindent \textbf{Action:} Instant

\noindent \textbf{Cost:} 1 Wisp

\noindent \textbf{Dice Pool:} Wits + Empathy

\noindent \textbf{Duration:} varies \\

\noindent The Princess delays a Charm's effects. She must touch the intended target, then use another Charm on him; the second Charm does not take effect immediately, instead the target gets the Held Charm condition for a time depending on her successes. She may choose to release the delayed Charm, allowing it to take effect, as an instant action at any time; if she doesn't release it when this Charm expires, the delayed Charm dissipates without effect. Alternately, instead of creating a delayed Charm that she may release herself, the Princess may set a condition that, if met, releases it automatically, to lengthen the time that Charm remains suspended; the more likely the condition is to occur, the longer the suspension lasts.

The Princess must tell the target what will happen when the suspended Charm takes effect, and if she sets a condition, she must tell the target what it is; but she can be as cryptic (\textquotedblleft\, When all eyes turn toward you, you'll find the strength to carry on") or as direct (\textquotedblleft\, Hey, jackass! Try stealing someone's purse again, and you're going to get set on fire!") as she wishes. She can keep up to her Inner Light in Charms suspended at once -- once she reaches that limit, she must release a Charm before she may use this Charm again.

In addition to either method of triggering the Charm the Princess may also set a condition in which the Charm vanishes without activating (\textquotedblleft\, Turn yourself in to the police by midnight or you'll be set on fire!\textquotedblright). 

\begin{myindentpar}{10pt}\textbf{Upgrade: Inanimate}

The Princess can place Held Charms on things other than living beings. She could for example enchant a corrupt lawyer's bag to teleport to her hands with Up In Smoke as soon as someone puts a laptop in it.

\textbf{Upgrade: Repeating}

The Princess may declare that her Charm will activate every time the condition is met. Each activation beyond the first requires an additional Success on the Charm's activation roll.\end{myindentpar}

\subsubsection*{Resting Place (Govern \textbullet\textbullet\textbullet, Lacrima \textbullet\textbullet\textbullet)}

\noindent \textbf{Action:} Full turn, Presence + Occult (vs Composure + Supernatural Advantage)

\noindent \textbf{Cost:} 2 Wisps

\noindent \textbf{Duration:} Inner Light in days

With access to both a ghost and any object a Raven can bind a new anchor for the ghost, applying the Anchor Condition to a target of her choice. This is temporary and only with great and constant effort can a Princess keep a loved one on this plane, more commonly it is used by the Followers of Tears to position their ghostly retainers where they can be of greatest service to the Last Empress. When used on an existing Anchor Resting Place can apply the Open condition. 

If the target is a living being he may resist the charm by rolling Composure + Supernatural Advantage, inanimate objects have no roll to resist. 

It should be noted that while ghosts can normally teleport to an anchor, the defences around Alhambra prevent them from crossing the boundary of the fortress city.


\begin{myindentpar}{10pt} \emph{Dramatic Failure:} The Noble offends the ghost; it either attacks her or runs from her.

\emph{Failure:} The ghost is not anchored to the object

\emph{Success:}The object gains the Anchor Condition [CofD 133] linked to the ghost for a number of days equal to the Princess’ Inner Light.

\emph{Exceptional Success:}	 The ghost finds manifesting near the object an easy feat. The new anchor gains the Open Condition.

\end{myindentpar}

\subsubsection*{Unweaving (Govern \textbullet\textbullet\textbullet\textbullet)}

\myframe{\textbf{Disciplines, Gifts and Contracts. Oh My!}

\vspace*{6pt}

Can a Princess unravel a Gift, or unpick a Contract? Well no. By default a Princess can only use Unweaving on magic created by Princesses, the Dark and other things found in the Princess books. Even when a Gift is mechanically similar to a Charm they are metaphysically different enough that a Princess cannot unpick the threads and end the magic.

\vspace*{6pt}

This is true, unless you, the Storyteller, decides it is not. Allowing Princesses to undo the magic of other's is certainly an advantage over other creatures, but if all the players are Princesses or the other creatures are given an equivalent ability to undo Charms this might not be a problem. You might choose to allow Unweaving to work against all forms of magic. Against foreign magic she rolls Occult (or Science against Geniuses), not Empathy, at say a -2 penalty for targets unrelated to Princesses (waive the Penalty if the Princess belongs to an appropriate Embassy, or make Embassy membership a prerequisite if you prefer).}

\noindent \textbf{Action:} Reactive, Instant, or Extended

\noindent \textbf{Dice Pool:} Clash of Wills or Dexterity + Empathy (5 minutes/roll, Threshold = Special )

\noindent Cost 2 Wisps\\

To unravel magical defences, to unpick a curse upon a beloved little sister, to tear apart a hostile Charm flying at you. There are many reasons why a Princess might need to unweave the Charms and magic of another. This Charm allows her to do so. The Princess may choose to Invoke this Charm as an Reactive, Instant, or Extended action depending on the situation and, difficulty of the task ahead. 

If invoked reactively the Princess grabs hold of the unfinished magic and tries to rip it apart while her opponent tries to hold the magic together. In short, Unweaving lets the Princess trigger a Clash of Wills at any time her opponent casts a spell on a target within arms reach.

An enchantment that has been completed and taken hold is tougher. Instead of a Contested Action the Princess must score more Successes than her opponent's Clash of Wills dicepool. She can attempt to grab the magic magic and rip it apart as an Instant action, or she can delicately unweave it thread by thread as an Extended action. 

Unweaving can only be used against \textquotedblleft magic power\textquotedblright\, abilities with a duration that lasts longer than a Turn. Innate abilities such as Transformation or Sensitivity are unaffected. The Princess also needs to be able to touch the magic, usually this means being within the affected area or within arms reach of the target. 

When used against Ephemeral Beings, such as Dreamlanders, Unweaving can be used to undo the effects of Influences and Numina. Unweaving cannot be used to undo Manifestations, it can remove Manifestatinon Conditions if they were created by an appropriate method. For example, Unweaving can remove the Anchor condition if was created with the Charm Resting Place, an Infleunce or a Numina. It could not remove the condition from a natural Anchor such as a ghost's old bones. 

\begin{myindentpar}{10pt}    \emph{Dramatic Failure:} The Princess gets her magic into a horrible tangle, and is at -2 to perform Unweaving for the rest of the scene.

    \emph{Failure:} The Princess makes no progress.
    
    \emph{Success:} Progress is made, when enough Successes are reached the target magic fall apart.
    
    \emph{Exceptional Success:} In addition to making great Progress, the Princess also learns some detail about the magic's origin, or why this thing was enchanted. Take the Informed Condition.
    
    Suggested Modifiers: The target magic is cast on a human (including Sworn and Princesses) (+2); The target magic is cast on something other than a living being (-2); the target magic is a Charm (+1), the target magic is a Charm and the Princess knows a Charm from the same family (+2), the target magic is a Charm and the Princess knows it (+3); the Princess applies an emotionally appropriate Invocation, such as Fuoco to unpick magic that turns love to loathing or Acqua to remove a curse of ignorance (+2), the Princess applies an emotionally inappropriate Invocation (-2), the Princess applies an elementally appropriate Invocation, such as Acqua or Fuoco to extinguish a magical fire (+2), the Princess applies an elementally inappropriate Invocation (-2).\end{myindentpar}

\subsubsection*{Accept Fealty (Govern \textbullet\textbullet\textbullet\textbullet, Invocation \textbullet\textbullet\textbullet)}

\noindent \textbf{Action:} Extended, Presence + Persuasion - Intimacy (10 minutes/roll, threshold = target's Willpower)

\noindent \textbf{Cost:} 1 Wisp/roll, 1 Willpower dot.

\noindent \textbf{Duration:} Lasting \\

\noindent Through a Ceremonial induction the Princess can invite mortals to join her Court, becoming Sworn. The ceremony is typically held in a relatively quiet and isolated location. This is for pragmatic reasons, as the process of the Charm creates a rather impressive light show. For the Sworn, the ceremony is an enlightening experience, no pun intended. They see the image of the Queen they have chosen to serve, for a moment they share in everything the Queen means to the Princess accepting their fealty, and in that moment they share in the Princess' magic. When the ceremony ends a small spark of Light remains.

The target must understand what he is doing, and do it voluntarily; on an unknowing or unwilling target, the Charm fails. It also fails on mortals steeped in villainy; the target must not have Vice-Ridden. Each Queen has a different version of this Charm, and a Princess can learn or use only the one for her own Queen.

Note that while Accept Fealty subtracts Intimacy from it's dicepool it cannot be performed at a distance, and penalty is not reduced to -0 for having line of sight. Many Princesses will gladly swear a mortal into their Court as a favour to Princesses who don't know this Charm or belong to another Court, in exchange for a Bequest or a favour worth a dot of Willpower. They power through the Intimacy penalty through high attributes. 

\subsubsection*{I am Become Light (Govern \textbullet\textbullet\textbullet\textbullet\textbullet, Fuoco \textbullet\textbullet\textbullet\textbullet)}

\noindent \textbf{Action:} Instant 

\noindent \textbf{Dice Pool:} Presence + Empathy

\noindent \textbf{Cost:} 3 Wisps, 1 Willpower

\noindent \textbf{Duration:} 1 scene \\

\noindent A Blazing crimson light shines forth from the Princess' heart, glowing through her body and Regalia. The Queen of Swords' avatar may walk among things not of the light, and know that they are the ones at the disadvantage.

   \begin{myindentpar}{10pt} \emph{Dramatic Failure:} The Princess' phylactery shatters, and she reverts to mundane form. The normal procedures for obtaining a new phylactery must be followed.

    \emph{Failure:} White light scintillates from the Princess' clothes, but there is no further effect.

    \emph{Success:} The Princess goes through a second transformation, her normal Regalia replaced with ones of even greater purity and a golden light shines out from her heart. The shift releases a burst of the Light that burns away magics alien to it; all supernatural powers not of the Light with fewer successes than the Princess' roll within a radius of Inner Light + successes yards immediately end, if the successes for their activation were less than her successes. Powers that did not require activation remain intact. In addition the Princess gets both the Shining Heart Tilt, with the same activation successes and radius, which bathes the affected area in true sunlight as well as applying her activation successes as a penalty to all supernatural powers not of the Light. Finally Swords' avatar gains the Terrifying Tilt which affects all Creature's of the Dark except the Dethroned.  

    \emph{Exceptional Success:} The extra successes are their own reward.\end{myindentpar} 
    
\subsubsection*{Martyr (Govern \textbullet\textbullet\textbullet\textbullet\textbullet, Tempesta \textbullet\textbullet\textbullet\textbullet)}

\noindent \textbf{Action:} Instant

\noindent \textbf{Dice Pool:} Presence + Intimidation + the Princess' Health Boxes without Aggravated Damage - Inner Darkness + the Dethroned's Health Boxes without Aggravated Damage.

\noindent \textbf{Cost:} 2 Wisps, 1 Willpower. Using this Charm is suicide. \\

\noindent The Seraphic General is Hate, and what she hates is The Darkness and the Nobility who betrayed mankind to the Darkness. Most such filth can be found hiding in Alhambra like the cowards they are, but others fell deeper into despair. Their crowns were shattered, their titles stripped from them, they were Dethroned. 

The sad truth is that, much like Princesses, you can't really kill a Dethroned. They reincarnate. Driving a Dethroned away or killing will normally keep it away for a very long time but for a truly permanent solution you have to redeem the Princess it once was. 

This doesn’t sit right with the Court of Storms, they don't believe the fallen deserve redemption, and so they have their own method. Reaching deep into the Dethroned they grab hold of their soul, they incinerate their body and drag the Dethroned's rotten soul into the afterlife.

To use this Charm the Princess must touch their target. Note that after the Dethroned is killed it's body remains for around ten minutes or so, during this time Martyr can be cast and the Dethroned cannot resist the Charm. 

\begin{myindentpar}{10pt} \emph{Dramatic Failure:} The Princess dies for nothing, the Dethroned remains at large. 

    \emph{Failure:} The Princess takes Resistant Lethal Damage equal to the Dethroned's Inner Darkness, and the Dethroned takes Resistant Lethal Damage equal to the Princess' Inner Light. If this kills either of them the Charm dosn't affect what happens next. 

    \emph{Success:} The Princess grabs the Dethroned and both ignite with green fire. In seconds only ash remains. 

    \emph{Exceptional Success:} No additional effect.\end{myindentpar} 

The furies claim that the Dethroned's rotten soul will be dragged before the Queen to be burnt to nothing by the Her righteous fury while the martyr will remain as a part of the Queen of Storms and lend their strength to Her crusade. While there is some evidence that the Furies do join with their Queen, what happens to the Dethroned is unknown. Since no one has kept a record of which Dethroned were killed in this manner they can't even prove it permanently kills Dethroned. 

\subsection*{Inspire}
Inspire Charms lift people's hearts, sparks their passions, and exhorts them to action. Only Troubadours have affinity for them.

Many Inspire Charms list a performance, these Charms require the Princess to sing a song, do a dance, read poetry, or put on some other kind of show before she rolls to invoke the Charm. In essence invoking the Charm is an instant action but one which takes longer than a single turn. A Princess does \textit{not} need to do a performance in order to fill artwork created by Living Image with a charge of an Inspire Charm, nor is any performance required for the charm to take effect beyond how a person would normally appreciate art of that type. Unless stated otherwise, the Commonality modifier may be applied to any Inspire Charm which requires a Performance.

